{"text": "2.1.3 Shannon's Source Coding Theorem\n\nThe next question to ask is whether there is any other scheme that can achieve a better\n\ncompression rate than the scheme in (2.6). This question is the one that Shannon asked in\n\nhis\n\nrst coding theorem. To answer this question, we consider a more general information\n\nsource and introduce a notion of Shannon, the idea of the set of typical sequences .\n\nWe can represent a more general information source with a random variable Xwhose\n\nrealizations xareletters in an alphabetX. LetpX(x) be the probability mass function\n\nassociated with random variable X, so that the probability of realization xispX(x). Let\n\nH(X) denote the entropy of the information source:\n\nH(X)\u0011\u0000X\n\nx2XpX(x) log (pX(x)): (2.19)\n\nc\r2019 Mark M. Wilde Licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 3.0 Unported License\n\n2.1. DATA COMPRESSION 47\n\nThe entropy H(X) is also the entropy of the random variable X. Another way of writing it\n\nisH(p), but we use the more common notation H(X) throughout this book.\n\nThe information content i(X) of random variable Xis\n\ni(X)\u0011\u0000log (pX(X)); (2.20)\n\nand is itself a random variable. There is nothing wrong mathematically here with having\n\nrandom variable Xas the argument to the density function pX, though this expression may\n\nseem self-referential at a\n\nrst glance. This way of thinking turns out to be useful later.\n\nAgain, the expected information content of Xis equal to the entropy:\n\nEXf\u0000log (pX(X))g=H(X): (2.21)\n\nExercise 2.1.1 Show that the entropy of a uniform random variable is equal to logjXj,\n\nwherejXjis the size of the variable's alphabet.\n\nWe now turn to source coding the above information source. We could associate a binary\n\ncodeword for each symbol xas we did in the scheme in (2.6).", "embedding": [0.015273361, 0.032742232, 0.10158599, -0.01822133, -0.020189323, -0.0397109, -0.013978098, -0.035617366, -0.0329070